In the unaccessible sea of Bolivia, the memory of the coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over the resources of the 19th century is still alive.
These hopes are perhaps the greatest in decades. Bolivia is awaiting the judgment of the International Court of Justice. It is due to be issued on 1 October after a five-year trial.
“Bolivia’s actions are gaining momentum, and the inhabitants are unanimous, optimistic and counting on a favorable verdict,” said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians across the country will be together to watch the International Court of Justice meeting. They hope that the Hague-based organisation will recognise Bolivia’s claim and, after decades of fruitless talks, Chile will have to enter into negotiations to grant the state independent access to the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic president of Bolivia, who next year will face a controversial fight for reelection, also puts hope in a Monday's ruling.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific," he swore at the end of August.
However, some analysts argue that the chances of a favorable ruling for Bolivia are small and that even a favorable decision would not change much.
The United Nations body established in the Hague does not have the authority to grant Bolivia the territory of Chile. It also stated that it would not affect the findings of any talks.
As Paz Zárate, a Chilean specialist in international law, said, the decision of the International Court of Justice will be issued six months after the final arguments have been put forward.
Unfortunately, Bolivia's last four years could have taken the country away from its destination.
