John Edward: Language skills necessary for citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland continue to enjoy their scientific achievements – in 2018 they were able to boast further excellent results of exams, supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other social projects.
The schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), attended by more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, aim to ensure the best level of service provided to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare pupils for further and higher education, the career path they choose and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that has the opportunity to develop and implement a school-specific curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said: “If you speak to another man in a language he understands, then it goes into his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages are ranked first in league rankings, with the highest reporting rates for independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages received a higher A rating.
Data from 74 member schools of the SCIS showed that 72 percent of the students obtained a higher A rating in Mandarin and 72 percent of the German learners, 69 percent of the French and 63 percent of the Spanish learners also obtained an A rating.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, language learning, as subjects of choice, is conducted to the same extent as STEM learning (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) as part of curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills showed that 17 percent of the employers' lack of language skills was responsible for the difficulties in filling vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people for a career.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with a growing number of jobs requiring knowledge of languages,
Lifelong skills, such as learning a second language, will provide a great advantage in the future, regardless of the career development path chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to competition.
According to the 2013 YouGov survey of over 4000 British adults, 75% of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit rate of 15%.
Therefore, investing in teaching foreign languages is so important for children today.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of the developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in terms of its languages.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK in 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the child's interest, in independent schools there will always be many languages to choose from that will be taught by teaching staff specialised in this area.
Scottish independent schools are involved in creating a learning environment that will equip their children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, regardless of what their future may be.
At present, it cannot be denied that in an international business environment, languages are still crucial for the future of the country and must therefore be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth a wide choice, diversity and level.
It's just the right thing to do.
John Edward, Chairman of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
