North Korea says "strongly no" to unilateral disarmament without trust.
The Foreign Minister of North Korea said on Saturday during a speech at the United Nations that the non-abuse of sanctions only aggravates the lack of confidence in North Korea in the United States and there is no way that the country unilaterally gave up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
At the Annual General Assembly, Ri Yong Ho said that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test sites and commitment to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see any specific answer from the US", he said.
"Without trust in the United States there will be no guarantee of our national security and under such circumstances there will be no unilateral disarmament of North Korea."
While Ri repeated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's reluctance to "gradual" approach to denucleation, in which North Korea would be rewarded for its gradual action, its statement seemed significant because it did not reject unilateral denuclearisation as it did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Una and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the President-in-Office of the United States and the leader of North Korea, which took place on 12 June in Singapore, when Kim Jong Un committed to work for the “denuklerarisation of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump promised guarantees of the security of North Korea.
North Korea was awaiting the formal end of the Korean War (1950–1953), but the U.S. representative announced that Pyongyang had to give up nuclear weapons first.
Washington also resisted calls to alleviate severe international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "dencularisation in the first place" and increases the pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a forced manner, even opposing the signing of the "declaration of the end of the war", said Ri.
"The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is the dream of people who behave in an ignorant way towards us.
The problem, however, is that the lack of abolition of sanctions is exacerbated by our mistrust."
Ri did not mention the plans for the second summit between Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, which was discussed by the United States leader at the UN at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the Minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korea's leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, and added: "If South Korea were a party to denucleation and not the United States, then there was no impasse in the denucleation of the Korean Peninsula".
Mim this, the tone of Ri's speech was completely different compared to last year, when he said at the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korean missiles in the United States was inevitable after Mr Evil President Trump (Mr Evil Trump) called Kim Jong Una "rocket man" (the man of the rocket) on a suicide mission.
This year, at the United Nations Trump, which last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, he commended Kim Jong Un for his courage to take steps to disarm, but he also said that much work still needed to be done, and he also said that until North Korea was deprived of nuclear weapons, sanctions would not be lifted.
