Harvard students are taking a course on adequate rest
The new course at Harvard University this year provided all students with more sleep to combat the growing macho culture of learning by “all-night caffeine-driven students”.
Students from the best university in the world often have no idea of the basis for taking care of themselves.
Charles Cheisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create a course by giving a speech about the influence of sleep deprivation on science.
"After the speech, one girl came up to me and said, "Why is it only now that I'm in my senior year?"
She said that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," said The Telegraph.
During the course, which took place for the first time this year, it is explained to students how good sleep habits help to achieve good results in science and sport, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university health service, said that this course was decided to be introduced after it was stated that students had severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hourly course includes a number of interactive tasks.
One section includes an image of the dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercises and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deprivation affects sports results, as well as how important it is to maintain the regularity of sleep.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
The map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not cause an immediate change in student behaviour.
But we believe that they have the right to know — just as everyone has the right to know what health effects smoking brings”, added Professor Cheisler
The culture of pride from "all night long learning" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students means an ever-increasing problem of sleep deprivation.
Providing enough sleep of good quality should be a "secret weapon" for students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into hunger mode, and the student is constantly hungry," he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Cheisler develop a course after taking part in one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a course for the entire campus.
The next step, according to him, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study programme before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Cheisler recommended that students set a reminder alarm when they need to go to sleep and when they need to get up, and that they should be aware of the harmful influence of the "blue light" emitted by the screens of electronic devices and LED lighting, which can upset the daily rhythm and cause problems with falling asleep.
