A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “see” hostile cells.
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to “see” hostile cells and destroy them.
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognise hostile cells as part of the treatment.
This method consists in separating immune cells from the patient and changing them in the laboratory.
Then they can “see” a protein common to many cancers. Then they are re-injected into the body.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with various types of cancer.
In one woman treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system, the loss of ovarian cancer has been observed for more than 18 months.
The method is to separate immune cells from the patient, change them in the laboratory so that they can “see” a protein common to many cancers called HER2 and then re-inject the patient with these cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the American National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results indicate that this vaccine is very promising".
HER2 "powered the growth of several types of cancers", including breast, ovarian, lung and colon cancer, explained Prof. Berzofsky.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and teaching them to locate cancer cells worked in the treatment of a certain type of leukaemia.
