HIV/Aids: China has a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS.
More than 820,000 people affected by this problem, as reported by healthcare professionals in the country.
Only in the second quarter of 2018, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases have been transmitted sexually, which means a change in relation to the past.
Traditionally, HIV spreads rapidly in some parts of China as a result of blood transfusions.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been almost completely reduced, as Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 compared to one year.
Transmitting HIV by sex is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is widespread.
Given the conservative values of the country, research estimates that 70-90% of men having sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of transmission of the disease are due to insufficient protection when having sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has ensured widespread access to HIV medicines as part of its efforts to combat this problem.
Maxine Waters denies that a member of her team has revealed the data of Republican Senators — these are “dangerous lies” and “conspiracy theory”.
On Saturday, a member of the United States House of Representatives, Maxine Waters, rejected the allegations that a member of her team had posted personal data of three Republican senators on the Wikipedia website of the above-mentioned legislators.
A member of the Los Angeles Democratic Party assured that these accusations were made by experts and websites linked to "ultra-right wings".
“ Lies, lies, and even more vile lies,” reported Waters in a Twitter statement.
The public information reportedly contained home addresses and telephone numbers of U.S. senators Lindsey Graham from South Carolina and Mike Lee and Orrin Hatch from Utah.
It was posted on the Internet on Thursday by an unknown person on the Capitol Hill during a hearing with the Senate panel on allegations of sexual misconduct against the nominee for the Supreme Court, Brett Kavanaugh.
The leak took place some time after three senators questioned Kavanaugh's candidacy.
Conservative sites such as Gateway Pundit and RedState reported that the IP address identifying the source of the posts was linked to Waters’ office and published information about a member of the Waters team, according to Hill.
"This unsubstantiated charge is completely false and it is a hundred percent lie," continued Waters.
“A member of my team — whose identity, personal data and security have been compromised as a result of these fraudulent and false allegations — was in no way responsible for leaking this information.
This baseless charge is completely false and it is a hundred percent lie."
Waters’ statement quickly sparked criticism on the Internet, including Ari Fleischer, a former White House spokesman.
"This kind of denial is wrong," wrote Fleischer.
"This suggests that she does not have the right temperament to be a member of Congress.
When someone is accused of something they didn't do, they can't be angry.
He can't provoke you.
He can't question the motives of the defendant.
For that, he must remain calm."
Fleischer seemed to compare Waters' reaction to the Democratic criticism of Judge Kavanaugh, who was accused of being overly angry during the Thursday hearing.
Omar Navarro, a Republican candidate for mid-term elections to replace Waters, also expressed his thoughts on Twitter.
"If it's true, it's a big deal," he tweeted.
In her statement, Waters said that her office had notified "the competent authorities and law enforcement authorities of these fraudulent accusations".
"The perpetrators will be exposed and brought to legal responsibility for all their activities which pose a threat to any member of my team," she said.
Review of the movie Johnny English: Knockout — Spy parody with the weakened Rowan Atkinson
Looking for references to Brexit in every new British theme film has already become the norm. This seems to apply to the new part of the series of films of the genre of action and comedy "Johnny English", which began in 2003 with the film "Johnny English" and which returned to the screens of cinemas in 2011 with the film "Johnny English: Reactivation".
Will the self-loathing satire of how hopeless we are become the new export product of the country?
In any case, the incompetent Johnny English, who is always surprised by his rubber face, has again been licensed to screw up — his name, more than anything else, signals that he is an elaborate, comical creation designed for non-English speaking audiences.
He is, of course, a silly secret agent who, despite his bizarre tastes for smoothie glamour, has a little bit of Inspector Clouseau, a pinch of Jack Bean and a hint of this guy adding one note to the theme tune of the Chariots of Fire at the 2012 Olympic Games opening ceremony.
In the past, he was also a traveler and a world mystery man — Atkinson once played in the forgotten Barclaycard TV commercials, where he left chaos behind.
In the latest Johnny English series, there is one or two moments worth mentioning.
I really liked the scene where Johnny English was approaching the helicopter, dressed in medieval armor, while his helmet was rhythmically struck by rotor blades.
On the screen you can clearly see Atkinson's gift for physical comedy, but the sense of humor seems to be quite low flights and unnecessary, especially since nowadays also "serious" film brands, such as 007 and Mission Impossible, offer comedy elements as part of the film.
The humorous elements seem to be directed at children rather than adults — in my opinion, Johnny English’s crazy adventures are not as inventive and coherent as the gags in Atkinson’s silent films about Jasie Bean.
It has always been the current assumption that Britain is in serious trouble.
Cyberhacker penetrates the British supersecret network of spies, revealing the identity of all British operatives in the field — to the horror of an agent on duty, Kevin Eldon, who unfortunately played a small role.
This is the last drop in the Prime Minister's bitterness spell, which is a pompous, wasted figure already suffering from a nervous breakdown caused by a lack of political popularity: Emma Thompson is doing everything in her power by acting as Theresa May, but the script does not give her the opportunity to expand her wings.
Her intelligence advisors are telling her that she's gonna have to reinstate one of the retired agents because of the identity of all active spies.
And that means incompetent Johnny English himself, currently employed as a teacher at some fancy school, giving informal lessons on how to become a secret agent — a few good gags while giving English spy lessons.
English is called to Whitehall for a briefing, reconnecting with his former sidekick Bough, played again by Ben Miller.
Bough is now a married man associated with a submarine commander — a cheerful but somewhat tired character played by Vicki Pepperdine.
So Batman and Robin of the party in the secret service of Her Majesty return to action, meeting the beautiful femme fatale Ophelia Bulletova, a character played by Olga Kurylenko.
Meanwhile, the Prime Minister is dangerously overtaken by a charismatic tech billionaire who claims to be able to solve the UK's computer problems — the sinister Jason Volt, played by Jake Lacy.
English and Bough begin their crusade of absurd situations: dressed as waiters, they set the French restaurant on fire; they create chaos by sneaking on board the luxury yacht Volta; and English wreak havoc when using the virtual reality kit to get acquainted with the interior of the Volta house.
In this last sequence, all limitations disappear, but despite a nice and loud performance, the whole film is very similar to children's TV.
It's a typical medium.
As with other Johnny English films, I could not resist thinking: can the British film industry not give Rowanów Atkinson a role that would really suit his talent?
