What is the Global Citizen Festival event and has it contributed to any reduction in poverty?
This Saturday, the Global Citizen Festival will be held in New York City, with an annual musical event that boasts an impressive composition of stars and an equally impressive mission to eradicate global poverty.
For the seventh time, the Global Citizen Festival will visit tens of thousands of people arriving at Great Lawn in Central Park, not only to enjoy the performances of stars such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to support the achievement of the most important goal of this event, which is to eliminate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which was launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international group of activists to fight poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket for this event (unless you have decided to purchase a VIP ticket), the concert participants had to perform a number of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, sending an email to the world leader, making a phone call or other significant activities to help raise awareness about the goal of eradicating poverty.
But what success can Global Citizen boast over the 12 years remaining to achieve the goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a good way to convince them to require action, or another case of so-called "clitivism" when people feel they are doing something important by signing an online petition or posting a tweet?
Global Citizen claims that since 2011 it has recorded more than 19 million “actions” of people supporting the action, aiming to achieve many different goals.
It also claims that these actions have helped world leaders to make commitments and regulations worth more than USD 37 billion that are expected to affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements resulting from its activities, in which at least 10 billion dollars had already been paid or financed.
The group estimates that the funds secured so far have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a British partnership of investors and developers involved in “helping children to reach their full potential”, which promised to hand over 35 million dollars to Rwanda to help eradicate malnutrition in the country, after Global Citizen members sent over 4700 tweets.
"With the support of the British government, donors, national governments and members of the Global Citizen, such as you, we can make social injustice, such as malnutrition, fall into history" — Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition, during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The Group also said that, following more than 5000 actions calling on Britain to improve the quality of nutrition for mothers and children, the government announced funding for the Power of Nutrition project, which will reach 5 million women and children with nutritional problems.
For one of the most frequently asked questions on its website, which was "How can we be sure that extreme poverty will be eradicated?",
Global Citizen replied: “It will be a long and difficult road — sometimes we will stumble and fail.
But as with the great civil rights movements of our time and the fight against apartheid, we will succeed, because together we are stronger.
Janet Jackson, the Weekend, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B, Janelle Monáe are among the stars of this year's New York event, hosted by Deborah-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
The United States could use the Navy to “block” Russian energy exports — Secretary of Interior
Washington may “if necessary” resort to its Navy to prevent Russian energy from flowing into markets, including those in the Middle East, revealed the U.S. Secretary of Interior, Ryan Zinke — Washington Examiner.
Zinke argued that Russia’s involvement in Syria — especially where it works at the invitation of the legitimate government — was an excuse to explore new energy markets.
"I believe that the reason they are in the Middle East is because they want to mediate the energy trade, as is the case in Eastern Europe," he said.
According to the official, there are ways and means to solve this problem.
"The United States, thanks to its navy, has the opportunity to ensure that the maritime routes remain open and, if necessary, to create a blockade to ensure that their energy does not enter the market", he said.
Zinke spoke to the participants of the event organized by Consumer Energy Alliance, a non-profit group that describes itself as the "voice of the energy consumer" in the United States.
He also compared Washington's approach to Russia and Iran, pointing out that they are actually the same.
“The economic option of Iran and Russia is more or less to use and replace fuels,” he said, comparing Russia to “a pony that knows one trick” with an economy that is dependent on fossil fuels.
These statements were made at a time when the Trump administration continued its mission to increase the export of liquefied natural gas to Europe, which is much cheaper for European consumers compared to Russian gas.
To this end, Trump officials, including President Donald Trump of the United States, are trying to convince Germany to withdraw from the "inappropriate" project of the Nord Stream 2 pipeline, which according to Trump made Berlin a "slave" of Moscow.
Moscow has repeatedly stressed that the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline worth 11 billion dollars, which is intended to double the existing capacity to 110 billion cubic metres, is an economic project only.
The Kremlin argues that Washington's fierce opposition to this project is purely due to economic reasons and is an example of unfair competition.
"I believe that we share the view that energy cannot be a tool for exerting pressure and that consumers should be able to choose suppliers," said Russian energy minister Aleksandr Novak after meeting with US Energy Secretary Rick Perry in September in Moscow.
The position of the United States triggered a violent reaction by Germany, which confirmed its commitment to the project.
Germany's leading industrial organisation, the German Industry Federation (BDI), urged the United States not to interfere in EU energy policy and bilateral agreements between Berlin and Moscow.
“I think it’s a big problem when a third country interferes with our energy supply,” said Dieter Kempf, Head of the German Industry Federation (BDI), following a recent meeting between German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Russian President Vladimir Putin.
