18 States and District of Colombia support the fight against the new asylum policy
Eighteen states and the District of Colombia support the legal challenge for a new US policy that refuses to grant asylum to victims fleeing gang violence or domestic violence.
On Friday, representatives of the 18 states and the district filed an amicus curiæ letter in Washington to support an asylum seeker struggling with this policy, as reported by NBC News.
The full name of the plaintiff in Grace v. Sessions, which the American Civil Liberty Union filed in August against federal policy, was not disclosed.
She said that her partner “and his violent sons from the gang” abused her, but American officials rejected her asylum application on July 20.
She was arrested in Texas.
The state prosecutors who supported Grace described El Salvador, Honduras and Guatemala, where there are a large number of asylum seekers in the USA, as countries facing widespread problems with gangs and domestic violence.
The new US asylum policy repealed the 2014 Board of Immigration Appeals decision, which allowed undocumented immigrants fleeing domestic violence to apply for asylum.
Karl Racine, Attorney General of the District of Colombia, said in his statement on Friday that the new policy "is ignoring the state, federal and international laws that have been in force for decades".
"Federal law requires all asylum applications to be dealt with on the basis of specific facts and circumstances, and such a prohibition violates this principle", as stated in the amicus curic.
The prosecutors further argued in their letter that a policy refusing immigrants entry harms the economy of the United States, claiming that they could become entrepreneurs and "be a necessary workforce".
In June, Attorney General Jeff Sessions ordered immigration judges to stop giving asylum to victims of domestic violence and gang violence.
“Azil is available to those who leave their country of origin because of persecution or fear of racial, religious, national or because they belong to a particular social group or have such and not other political beliefs,” said the Sessions in his statement of 11 June on asylum policy.
