The United States Ambassador accuses China of “harassing” propaganda advertising.
A week after the official Chinese newspaper published a four-page commercial in an American daily newspaper that commended the mutual benefits of American-Chinese trade, the U.S. ambassador in China accused Beijing of using the American press to spread propaganda.
Last Wednesday, U.S. President Donald Trump referred to the China Daily pay-per-view in Des Moines Register, the most popular newspaper in the state of Iowa, accusing China of trying to interfere in the United States Congress elections on 6 November, China contradicts this allegation.
Trump's allegation that Beijing was trying to interfere with the U.S. elections confirmed what American officials said to Reuters that this is a new stage in Washington's escalation campaign to put pressure on China.
While it is normal for foreign governments to place commercials promoting trade with their countries, Beijing and Washington are currently conducting an escalation of the trade war, which has led to an increase in tariffs for reciprocal imports.
Chinese retaliatory tariffs at the beginning of the trade war were to affect exporters in states such as Iowa who supported the Trump Republican Party, said Chinese and American experts.
Terry Branstad, U.S. Ambassador to China and former Governor of the State of Iowa, a major exporter of agricultural products to China, said that Beijing has done harm to American workers, farmers and entrepreneurs.
Branstad stated in an article in the Sunday issue of Des Moines Register that China "is now starting to harass with double force, placing propaganda advertising in our own free press".
"By asserting its propaganda, the Chinese government enjoys a respected American tradition of free speech and free press, placing paid advertising in the Des Moines Register," wrote Branstad.
On the other hand, there will be no opposition in the newsstand in Beijing and no real reflection of the divergent views that the Chinese may have on the worrying economic direction taken by China, given that the media are under the strong control of the Chinese Communist Party," he wrote.
He added that “one of the most famous Chinese newspapers refused to publish” his article, although he did not say which newspaper.
