National Trust eavesdropping on the secret life of bats
New research on the Scottish Highlands estate is designed to show how bats use the landscape for food.
Research is expected to shed new light on the behaviour of these exceptional flying mammals and help to steer future efforts to protect them.
Research conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will concern midgets and small ones, as well as brown bats with long ears and bats from the Red Night family in Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
In key locations around the property special recorders will be placed to track the activity of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out field studies using portable detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all recordings is intended to determine the frequency of signals sent by bats and the behaviour of individual species.
A habitat map and a report will then be developed to create a detailed picture of their landscape behaviour.
Rob Dewar, NTS's conservation advisor, hopes that the results will reveal which habitat areas are the most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help identify the benefits of habitat management, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best ways to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have decreased significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the girdles and loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can flies and certain chemicals used in building materials, and even domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of night hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a complex technique of echolocation to search for worms and obstacles in their path.
The NTS organization, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly carry out tests, inspections of the girdle, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even founded the first and only bat reserve in Scotland on the property Three in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten Scottish bat species.
David Thompson, the estate manager, says it's the perfect territory for bats.
"Three has a great area for bats," he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and excellent habitats.
However, there are still many unknowns about bats. The work we do here and in other properties will help us to better understand what they need to develop."
It stresses the importance of bat control before the maintenance work is carried out in the estates, since the involuntary destruction of one girdle can kill up to 400 females and young, which could result in the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected — killing, harassing, or disturbing them, and destroying their girdles is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and in the case of many species, we don't even know how their populations are doing."
