Information about the flower — in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota the density of the plankton decreases
Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission's latest report shows an overall decline in plankton density in some parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the presence of a speckled flower has been reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting that its density is decreasing.
It stretches about 200 miles [209 km] of coastline from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The blooms can be found about 16 kilometres from the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
The flower was also seen in Pasco County.
Last week there was an average concentration of plankton off the coast and in the waters of Pinellas County, low to medium off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high in Manatee County, natural to high off the coast and Sarasota County, natural to medium in Charlotte County, natural to high off the coast and Lee County and low in Collier County.
In Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier, cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported.
Last week, however, they were not reported in northwest Florida.
